and gaming can be leveraged for significant social benefit."}, "TVN24": {"Sport": "", "Culture": "A new edition of the classic Polish comic ''Kajko i Kokosz - Wielki Turniej'' has been released in a landmark linguistic adaptation. This special version marks the first time the series has been translated into the traditional Warsaw dialect. The publication is intended as a tribute to the legendary comic book artist Janusz Christa and the linguistic heritage of the capital city. Collectors and new readers alike can now experience the adventures of the iconic warriors through a local cultural lens. This release highlights the enduring relevance of classic Polish comics and their ability to be reimagined for modern audiences. It stands as a significant contribution to preserving both regional slang and national pop-culture history.", "Economy": "The European Parliament voted to uphold airline passenger rights, maintaining the requirement for compensation after flight delays of three hours despite pressure from member states. Global markets reacted positively to President Donald Trump''s announcement that he would not implement scheduled tariffs on European countries. In Poland, the Ministry of Climate is preparing for potential changes to the deposit system, which may soon include small glass alcohol bottles. Meanwhile, the beauty industry is experiencing a massive surge in global sales despite rising costs of living affecting other sectors. Reports indicate that annual global spending on cosmetic products has reached hundreds of billions of dollars. These developments show a complex landscape of regulatory protections, trade shifts, and resilient consumer spending habits.", "Society": "Severe winter weather has prompted IMGW to issue frost warnings for over half of Poland, with temperatures expected to drop below -20 degrees Celsius. In domestic news, a missing 12-year-old boy from Koczargi Stare was found safe in Warsaw after an intensive police search. Public safety incidents included an evacuation of 200 people at Chopin Airport due to an unattended bag and a tragic hit-and-run in Bytom. Labor Minister Agnieszka Dziemianowicz-Bąk announced reforms to strengthen the National Labour Inspectorate and improve worker protections in courts. Internationally, a tourist helicopter crashed on a volcano in Japan, while residents in Illinois organized a fundraiser to find new mates for lonely swans. Other local stories included the birth of a mouse-deer at the Warsaw Zoo and the appearance of giant ice formations on Baltic beaches.", "Politics": "Donald Trump announced that Vladimir Putin accepted an invitation to the Peace Council, while Russian officials are currently reviewing the proposal. Polish President Karol Nawrocki clarified that Poland''s participation in this initiative would require approval from the national parliament and government. Both ruling and opposition politicians in Poland have expressed the need for a cautious and unified approach regarding the Peace Council to ensure the best outcome for the country. At the World Economic Forum in Davos, Trump delivered a wide-ranging speech where he discussed Greenland and criticized other world leaders like Emmanuel Macron. He also issued a reminder to the Canadian Prime Minister about the economic dependence of Canada on the United States. Additionally, Trump''s decision to suspend planned tariffs on European goods led to significant reactions in global financial markets.", "Technology": ""}, "Interia": {"Sport": "Sports coverage is currently centered on high-profile football events and the performance of star players like Robert Lewandowski. Digital simulations are being used to predict the outcome of FC Barcelona''s Champions League clash against Slavia Prague, suggesting a strong performance for the Polish striker. Fans and analysts alike are focused on whether Lewandowski can continue his impressive scoring streak in elite European competition. This trend reflects the growing intersection between professional sports and technological analytics used to engage the fanbase. While other major sporting events are ongoing, the focus remains on top-tier European football matches involving Polish national icons. The sports world continues to monitor player conditions and team strategies ahead of these critical mid-season fixtures.", "Culture": "Cultural news features a blend of historical discoveries and modern media developments. Netflix has unveiled plans for four new Polish original productions for 2026, including its first medical drama and stories inspired by true events. In the religious sphere, Pope Leon XIV has reached out to Polish believers with a message emphasizing Christian values and human kindness. Archaeological projects have made significant finds, including an Anglo-Saxon ''center of power'' in England and unprecedented Roman military camps in eastern Germany. Philanthropy and technology merged as a unique Lego set of the Polish Maria nuclear reactor was auctioned for charity. Educational interest in the Arctic has also peaked, with new resources detailing the cultural and geographical secrets of Greenland. These stories highlight a diverse interest in heritage, faith, and local creative content.", "Economy": "Economic news is highlighted by a major procedural delay in the Mercosur trade agreement, which has been referred to the EU Court of Justice for a compatibility check. This move, supported by the European Parliament, could postpone the implementation of the trade deal by up to two years and has drawn criticism from German officials. In the transportation sector, Polish rail operator Polregio reported a record-breaking year with over 100 million passengers served in 2025. Additionally, the aviation market sees increased competition as Ryanair announces new routes from Poland to Albania, mirroring previous moves by Wizz Air. These developments indicate a period of regulatory hurdles for global trade alongside robust growth in regional travel demand. The gaming industry also faces economic pressure, with reports of rising console prices for the upcoming Nintendo Switch 2 in 2026.", "Society": "Society is facing various challenges ranging from public health issues to natural disasters. Residents in several Polish regions were issued emergency alerts due to dangerous levels of smog, while Italy continues to battle the destructive effects of Cyclone Harry. Public safety has been highlighted by the heroic actions of a WOT soldier who saved a woman''s life on a train and a new initiative to distribute free smoke detectors in Kujawsko-Pomorskie. Tragic incidents, such as a mall collapse in Russia and a fatal accident involving a teenager at a military park, have sparked investigations into safety regulations. Health officials in the U.S. are also on high alert as a measles outbreak threatens to strip the country of its disease-free status. On a lighter note, travel patterns for 2026 show Poles increasingly opting for southern climates during winter breaks. Finally, surveys from the Vatican reveal significant dissatisfaction among its lay workforce, marking a first for the city-state.", "Politics": "International relations are strained as Donald Trump uses the Davos summit to demand negotiations over Greenland and criticize allies for exploiting the United States. Tensions with Iran have escalated following their recent missile tests, prompting the U.S. to deploy additional forces and advanced weaponry to the Middle East. In Poland, domestic politics are marked by legal investigations into judicial figures and heated confrontations at the National Council of the Judiciary (KRS) involving police and members of parliament. Ukraine remains a focal point of geopolitical concern, with discussions in Davos revolving around potential peace plans and the country''s survival through the winter. European leaders are also grappling with potential trade wars and the implications of the Mercosur agreement being referred to the EU Court of Justice. Meanwhile, Russia faces internal political shifts as figures like Dmitry Medvedev seek new roles within the Duma. Security experts are also monitoring Russian activities in the Arctic, which some consider more dangerous than current territorial disputes.", "Technology": "The technology and gaming sectors are experiencing significant turbulence and innovation. Ubisoft has announced a major restructuring involving the cancellation of several projects, including the Prince of Persia remake, and the closure of two studios. In contrast, CD Projekt RED is moving forward with a massive budget for the next Witcher installment, while Xbox prepares for its 2026 Developer Direct. Military technology is also advancing, with tests of the Polish KUNA autonomous platform and the British Proteus śmigłowiec demonstrating the future of unmanned warfare. Consumer tech updates include new e-ID management in the mObywatel app and age verification systems for ChatGPT users. Scientific research has also challenged historical views, suggesting humans may possess up to 33 distinct senses. Furthermore, China is developing the Xuntian space telescope to rival Hubble''s capabilities by 2027."}, "NewYorkTimes": {"Sport": "The sports world is grappling with the tangible effects of climate change and evolving ethical challenges in professional competition. Recent research indicates that future Winter Olympic Games will require significantly higher altitudes and dispersed venues to cope with rising global temperatures and shrinking snow cover. This environmental shift is forcing organizers to rethink the logistical and geographic requirements for hosting major winter sporting events. On the business side, the ubiquity of sports-betting scandals has raised questions about long-term fan engagement and the integrity of professional leagues. From environmental adaptation to the ethics of gambling, these developments signal a transformative period for the infrastructure and culture of modern athletics.", "Culture": "Cultural shifts are being observed through changes in popular media and the resilience of artistic institutions. Longtime judge Prue Leith announced her departure from ''The Great British Baking Show,'' marking the end of a significant era for the beloved international television competition. In France, the reopening of the historic La Clef Cinema, now run by volunteers with support from legendary filmmakers, highlights a grassroots effort to preserve art-house culture. Meanwhile, music has become a powerful tool for protest, with a pro-Greenland song becoming an anthem against annexation and a new rhythm going viral in Venezuela. These stories reflect how individual personalities and collective artistic movements continue to shape the global cultural landscape.", "Economy": "The global economy is currently navigating significant volatility driven by trade disputes and legal battles over central bank independence. The Supreme Court is weighing a landmark case regarding President Trump’s attempt to fire Federal Reserve Governor Lisa Cook, a decision that could profoundly impact the Fed''s autonomy. Meanwhile, international markets have fluctuated in response to threats of escalating tariffs against European and Canadian partners, though stocks eventually stabilized after recent de-escalations. In the energy sector, Japan is taking steps to restart the world''s largest nuclear plant to balance clean energy needs with post-Fukushima safety concerns. Furthermore, trade agreements between Europe and South America have stalled, reflecting broader anxieties about shifting global trade alliances and protectionist policies. Budget travelers and luxury seekers alike are facing a fragmented pricing landscape as they plan for future expenditures.", "Society": "Societal trends are currently defined by shifting travel habits, significant legal testimonies, and developments in public safety. Travelers are increasingly moving away from traditional summer vacations in favor of ''microvacations'' and off-season trips to avoid extreme weather and crowds. High-profile legal events, such as Prince Harry’s emotional testimony regarding the traumatic impact of news coverage, underscore the ongoing tension between public figures and the media. In public health, a revolutionary template for treating female victims of violence is gaining traction in France, offering a more holistic approach to medical care. Additionally, tragic incidents like the train crash in Spain and ongoing safety concerns regarding ride-sharing services like Uber continue to drive conversations about infrastructure and corporate responsibility. The media landscape also sees growth with new daily newsletters attempting to cut through the noise of online news.", "Politics": "President Trump’s recent activities at the World Economic Forum in Davos have centered on escalating geopolitical tensions and unconventional diplomatic maneuvers. A significant portion of the political news cycle covers his insistence on acquiring Greenland, which has sparked protests among locals and strained relations with European allies. Domestically, the administration has faced various legal challenges, including a bipartisan House panel vote to hold the Clintons in contempt and the deployment of military police to Minnesota. Additionally, policy shifts at the E.P.A. have come under fire for discontinuing the practice of valuing human life in cost-benefit analyses for pollution rules. These events underscore a period of intense political friction both internationally and within the United States government. The administration also continues to grapple with foreign policy pivots in Syria and ongoing tensions with China regarding Taiwan''s defense funding.", "Technology": "The integration of facial recognition technology is rapidly expanding at airport security and immigration checkpoints to streamline the traveler experience, despite ongoing privacy concerns. Simultaneously, job seekers are challenging the transparency of artificial intelligence used in hiring processes, with a new lawsuit likening AI screening to credit agency reporting. These developments highlight a broader shift toward automated identification and evaluation systems in both the public and private sectors. While these tools promise efficiency, they face increasing legal and ethical scrutiny regarding data protection and ''black box'' decision-making. The intersection of emerging tech and individual rights remains a central theme in current technological discourse."}}', '{"BBC": {"Sport": 2, "Culture": 4, "Economy": 0, "Society": 4, "Politics": 5, "Technology": 1}, "TVN24": {"Sport": 0, "Culture": 1, "Economy": 4, "Society": 12, "Politics": 6, "Technology": 0}, "Interia": {"Sport": 1, "Culture": 7, "Economy": 3, "Society": 17, "Politics": 34, "Technology": 28}, "NewYorkTimes": {"Sport": 3, "Culture": 4, "Economy": 14, "Society": 17, "Politics": 32, "Technology": 3}}') ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO daily_summaries VALUES (14, CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '10 days', '{"BBC": {"Sport": "In the world of cricket, Sri Lanka demonstrated a powerful performance, accelerating significantly in the last 10 overs against England during their first One-Day International in Colombo. Meanwhile, Aston Villa manager Unai Emery has articulated his ambition to win the Europa League, despite publicly ruling out his team as Premier League title contenders. His focus is clearly directed towards achieving European glory after successfully guiding his team to the last 16 of the competition. These updates highlight both thrilling athletic contests and the strategic aspirations of professional sports teams.", "Culture": "Significant discoveries are prompting a re-evaluation of humanity''s creative timeline, with the identification of the world''s oldest known cave painting – a stencilled red claw hand found on Indonesia''s Sulawesi island. In film, Charlie Chaplin''s silent comedy ''City Lights'' continues to be lauded as one of cinema''s greatest achievements, with its iconic final shot playing a crucial role in its enduring reputation. Moving into contemporary entertainment, music fans are anticipating Harry Styles'' global tour, announced ahead of his fourth album release. The tour promises special guests, including Shania Twain, showcasing the vibrant and evolving landscape of global music culture. These articles span ancient artistic expression, classic cinematic masterpieces, and modern musical tours, reflecting the diverse facets of human creativity.", "Economy": "Tiny Slovakia has remarkably transformed into a major car-making heavyweight, demonstrating significant economic growth in its manufacturing sector. The country now produces nearly a million cars annually, hosting substantial factories for prominent international automotive companies such as Kia and Volkswagen. This impressive output has solidified Slovakia''s position as a key player in the global automotive industry. This development underscores the country''s industrial capacity and its successful integration into global supply chains, contributing substantially to its national economy. Its strategic location and skilled workforce have been key factors in attracting such significant foreign investment and establishing its reputation.", "Society": "Societies worldwide are navigating a range of natural phenomena and their profound societal impacts. Scientists have only recently described a mysterious mushroom that is found globally and consistently induces visions of tiny humans in those who encounter it. Simultaneously, extreme weather events are causing widespread disruption; a tourist vividly recounted fleeing a landslide in New Zealand, while Russia''s Far East endured its heaviest snowfall in 60 years, leaving cars and people stranded, with scientists suggesting a link to climate change. The US is also bracing for a massive winter storm, expected to bring extensive snow and ice, prompting officials to warn travellers of significant delays. In an interesting urban environmental shift, Bangkok''s giant monitor lizards, once confined to the city''s outskirts, are now flourishing in parks and canals, becoming an unexpected part of the visitor experience and illustrating changing human-wildlife dynamics within urban environments.", "Politics": "Global political developments include Uganda''s losing presidential candidate, Bobi Wine, opting not to challenge election results in court, citing an independent judiciary and calling for peaceful change instead. At the World Economic Forum in Davos, former US President Trump discussed a ''framework of a future deal'' on Greenland and backed off tariff threats, later suggesting a possible ''forever'' deal for the island. During the same event, Trump also held a charter-signing ceremony for a ''new international oversight body,'' though several key international allies were notably absent. Furthermore, the UN is preparing to take over the al-Hol camp in Syria, which houses families associated with IS, following the withdrawal of Kurdish-led forces and amidst ''tense and volatile'' conditions, signaling a significant international political and humanitarian intervention.", "Technology": "A Russian cosmonaut captured a stunning aurora from space during one of the largest solar storms in over two decades, showcasing advanced space photography. In another technological application, AI ''patients'' are now being utilized to train student doctors, featuring realistic faces and voices for interactive learning experiences. This innovative use of artificial intelligence aims to provide medical students with practical training similar to real-life patient interactions. These developments highlight both human exploration beyond Earth and the practical, educational applications of cutting-edge AI in professional training. The integration of AI in education represents a significant step forward in preparing future medical professionals."}, "TVN24": {"Sport": "", "Culture": "A unique charity auction for the Great Orchestra of Christmas Charity (WOŚP) offers participants the exclusive opportunity to attend the premiere of a new film adaptation of \"Lalka,\" with the lead actress, Kamila Urzędowska, personally inviting bids. This philanthropic event successfully merges cultural promotion with a significant charitable cause, raising public engagement. Separately, a historic granary, famously linked to the epic \"Pan Tadeusz,\" surprisingly failed to find buyers at a bailiff auction, indicating underlying financial and legal challenges for its current owners despite its cultural value. In a fascinating archaeological discovery, workers excavating a pond near Płock unearthed a significant fragment of a steppe bison''s skull. This rare find provides a tangible link to ancient fauna and offers valuable insight into the region''s rich natural history.", "Economy": "The Polish banking sector is undergoing a significant change as Santander Bank Polska prepares to rename itself Erste Bank Polska. This rebranding is a direct consequence of a major ownership shift, following Erste''s acquisition of approximately 49% of Santander Bank Polska''s shares earlier in January. The move reflects a new strategic direction for the institution under its updated corporate identity. This event highlights ongoing consolidation and international investment trends within the European financial industry. This strategic change is expected to reshape the competitive landscape within the Polish banking market.", "Society": "Warsaw experienced a concerning rise in traffic fatalities last year, with 28 lives lost, a quarter of which were attributed to drunk driving. Across Poland, severe winter conditions triggered multiple IMGW warnings for frost, freezing rain, and slippery roads, notably causing Gdańsk Bay to freeze for the first time in five years. Natural disasters also brought tragedy, with fatal floods striking Greece and France, highlighting vulnerabilities to extreme weather events. Law enforcement dealt with various incidents, from the arrest of a man wanted for organized crime and drug trafficking to the rescue of a dog found frozen to the roadside. Societal concerns included immigration agents detaining a 5-year-old boy in the US, a significant lack of trust among Polish employees towards their superiors, and severe power outages impacting residents of new housing estates during cold weather. Furthermore, environmental ethics were brought to the forefront with a year-round fireworks ban in Wrocław and warnings against feeding wild animals, as human actions were shown to inadvertently attract predators and lead to calls for their culling.", "Politics": "Internal turmoil has gripped Poland 2050, with factions accusing each other of \"Belarusian standards\" and \"coup attempts\" amid efforts to reschedule leadership elections. The European Parliament decisively rejected a no-confidence vote against the European Commission over a trade agreement. Globally, Donald Trump''s activities garnered significant attention, from his repeated geographical error in Davos to the launch of a new \"Peace Council\" focusing on Gaza. German Chancellor Friedrich Merz affirmed strong transatlantic ties and noted Trump''s comments on Greenland, while US envoys also held talks with Vladimir Putin in Moscow. Trump is additionally suing JPMorgan Chase for $5 billion alleging political discrimination. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky described his meeting with Donald Trump in Davos as \"fruitful,\" as Polish Prime Minister Donald Tusk addressed a \"crisis\" in EU-US relations, urging patience and prioritizing Ukraine.", "Technology": "The consumer electronics market is bracing for a potential downturn, with analysts predicting a significant drop in sales of smartphones, computers, and consoles. This projected decline, which could be the first major market collapse in years, is primarily attributed to a sharp increase in the prices of semiconductor memory. Manufacturers are already passing these increased costs onto consumers. Separately, French gaming giant Ubisoft experienced a dramatic fall in its stock value following the announcement of a substantial company restructuring. This overhaul includes a new creative structure and the cancellation of six upcoming projects, among them one of its most anticipated games. The news reflects broader challenges and strategic shifts within the technology and gaming sectors."}, "Interia": {"Sport": "The world of esports is set to open a new chapter with the Intel Extreme Masters (IEM) tournament debuting in Krakow, marking a significant milestone after nearly two decades of prestigious competitions. In football news, Jan Bednarek was recognized in the latest Team of the Week (TOTW) in EA Sports FC 26, after scoring a crucial goal that secured FC Porto''s advancement to the semi-finals of the Portuguese Cup. These events highlight the growing prominence of competitive gaming and individual achievements in traditional sports within the entertainment sphere.", "Culture": "The gaming industry is bustling with new releases and developments; \"Fable\" and \"Forza Horizon 6\" received official presentations and gameplay reveals, while the Polish-developed \"StarRupture\" became an early 2026 bestseller. Other notable news includes Epic Games giving away \"Rustler,\" and \"Metroid Prime 4: Beyond\" being a key launch title for Nintendo Switch 2. However, the industry also faced challenges, like Bungie''s \"Marathon\" preorder glitch and Ubisoft''s stock crash after a major restructuring, indicating internal struggles. In film adaptations, the \"Silent Hill\" movie received harsh reviews, and a \"Pirates of the Caribbean\" director criticized Unreal Engine 5''s use in cinema. Beyond games, Amazon is expanding its TV series adaptations with \"Tomb Raider\" starring Sophie Turner and new cast announcements for \"God of War,\" despite Turner''s health struggles during training. Luxury gaming merchandise from \"Ghost of Yotei\" was also released, showcasing the expansive reach of gaming culture.", "Economy": "The economic landscape saw a significant downturn for Ubisoft, with its stock prices plummeting over 30% following a major restructuring that included project cancellations and delays. Meanwhile, Poland is witnessing new developments in its real estate sector with the construction of the AFI Tower in Warsaw, set to be the tallest in its complex. The strategic importance of rare earth metals is highlighted, akin to oil in the 20th century, driving geopolitical discussions as nations vie for control over these crucial resources for modern technologies. In the aviation sector, Polish Airlines LOT is modernizing its fleet with new Boeing 737 MAX 8 aircraft, signaling investment and expansion.", "Society": "Diverse societal issues grabbed headlines, from natural disasters like Cyclone Harry causing \"apocalyptic\" destruction in Southern Italy and Malta, to rare phenomena such as \"ice tsunamis\" observed on Poland''s Baltic coast. Public safety concerns emerged in Germany with a youth gang led by 11-year-old twins terrorizing Leipzig, and in Poland, two men tragically died in a construction accident in Żory, while a family died from carbon monoxide poisoning in Chełmno with a chimney sweep facing charges. Education topics included discussions on Minister Nowacka''s proposed changes to school appearance rules and the longer list of public questions for Matura 2026. Kiev continues to face a humanitarian crisis with thousands of buildings lacking heating and electricity after Russian attacks, prompting international aid. Other notable events included student protests in Serbia over a professor''s dismissal and recurring train accidents in Spain, alongside an ongoing cold case investigation into Iwona Wieczorek''s disappearance in Poland. Reports also covered a former steward who defrauded airlines for free flights and warnings about severe winter conditions impacting transportation in Japan.", "Politics": "Recent political discussions have been heavily influenced by Donald Trump and the newly formed Council of Peace, with Tusk praising cooperation with Nawrocki and Trump announcing the council''s success for \"building peace according to international law.\" The agreement regarding Greenland, involving the US, Denmark, and the island''s sovereignty, has sparked varied reactions from NATO leaders and Prime Ministers, while Putin also commented on Greenland, comparing it to Alaska. Ukraine''s President Zelensky addressed concerns about Europe''s security and NATO''s reliance on the US, urging for stronger European defense, and also critically commented on Orban''s pro-Russian stance. Diplomatic tensions persist, with Germany expelling a Russian diplomat and Ukraine claiming successful strikes on Russian oil infrastructure and airfields. Domestically, Poland faces decisions regarding joining the Council of Peace, experiencing internal political turmoil within Poland 2050, and dealing with border incidents involving drones from Belarus. Other political news includes controversies around US immigration policies, the Clintons facing charges of contempt of Congress, and a German MP''s provocative remarks about reparations from Poland.", "Technology": "Technological advancements are rapidly progressing across various sectors, with Microsoft optimizing its Xbox application for ARM processors, and Volvo unveiling the EX60, its first electric car featuring Google Gemini AI, boasting a range over 800 km. In the space industry, Blue Origin announced TeraWave, its satellite internet constellation with over 5,400 satellites, directly competing with Starlink, while Vast Space is making strides towards launching Haven-1, potentially the first private space station. Renault is venturing into military production, collaborating to build long-range drones for Ukraine, demonstrating the crossover of automotive and defense tech. Furthermore, Stadler is testing a massive hybrid locomotive in Poland, signaling innovations in rail transport, and KLM is enhancing passenger experience by offering free in-flight Wi-Fi on European routes. The digital world is also seeing shifts as Netflix plans TikTok-like vertical videos for its mobile app, and YouTube confronts the rise of AI-generated content with new policies. The impact of tech giants is also highlighted by a book on Nvidia''s history."}, "NewYorkTimes": {"Sport": "", "Culture": "In the world of arts and entertainment, the highly anticipated nominations for the 98th Academy Awards were officially announced. This revelation presented the complete roster of films and individuals who will be competing for various prestigious Oscar accolades. The cultural event sets the stage for the upcoming grand ceremony, scheduled to air on March 15, where the ultimate winners will be celebrated and recognized for their cinematic achievements.", "Economy": "The global economic environment reflected significant shifts and considerable unpredictability, largely influenced by President Trump''s policies. The Energy Department announced the cancellation of $30 billion in clean energy loans, underscoring a dramatic change in the nation''s energy policy direction. At the prestigious World Economic Forum in Davos, discussions around climate change notably receded from being a top business priority, signaling a reorientation of focus within the global business community. President Trump''s unpredictable actions, such as his quick reversal on tariffs concerning Greenland, exemplified his willingness to disrupt established international trade agreements and the broader global economic order, even those he previously shaped. This behavior left European leaders unsettled, prompting them to actively seek strategies to assert their economic strength and leverage in response to the U.S. administration''s perceived disrespect.", "Society": "An unexpected incident involving a high-profile individual''s family captured public attention. During a trial, details emerged regarding an emergency call made by Barron Trump, President Trump’s youngest son, to U.K. police. He reportedly witnessed a woman being assaulted during a video call, bringing a private and potentially distressing event into the public sphere.", "Politics": "The political landscape was markedly shaped by President Trump''s distinctive and often contentious policies, both domestically and internationally. Domestically, the National Park Service controversially removed a climate change sign from Fort Sumter, a site vulnerable to rising seas, while the EPA revived a plan to end animal testing by 2035. New U.S. rules aimed to expedite seafloor mining, drawing corporate applause but raising environmental questions, and the arrest of a school superintendent on fraud and immigration charges highlighted issues of public integrity. Internationally, President Trump''s ''whipsaw approach'' to global affairs, exemplified by his ''Board of Peace'' initiative and shifting stances on Greenland, left European allies questioning U.S. reliability and the established international order. Negotiations surrounding Greenland included proposals for sovereign U.S. bases and restrictions on Russian influence, meeting strong opposition from Denmark over sovereignty. Ukrainian President Zelensky, meanwhile, issued a sharp rebuke to European leaders at Davos, urging them to intensify support or risk being marginalized.", "Technology": "The technology sector saw a mix of practical advice, ethical concerns, and industry drama. Guidance was offered on managing obsolete electronic gadgets, encouraging users to either refurbish them or responsibly dispose of them after retrieving any data. More controversially, Elon Musk''s Grok A.I. chatbot faced significant criticism following new estimates revealing it generated millions of sexualized images, with a substantial percentage depicting women. The increasing adoption of artificial intelligence tools in educational environments also sparked discussions among readers about its impact on teaching and learning. Additionally, a new A.I. start-up, Thinking Machines, became the center of Silicon Valley drama due to internal turmoil, including defections and power struggles. Lastly, even common tech applications like iPhone and Android weather apps grappled with accurately forecasting complex winter storms, highlighting the ongoing challenges in predictive technology."}}', '{"BBC": {"Sport": 2, "Culture": 3, "Economy": 1, "Society": 5, "Politics": 4, "Technology": 2}, "TVN24": {"Sport": 0, "Culture": 3, "Economy": 1, "Society": 24, "Politics": 16, "Technology": 2}, "Interia": {"Sport": 2, "Culture": 18, "Economy": 4, "Society": 23, "Politics": 39, "Technology": 11}, "NewYorkTimes": {"Sport": 0, "Culture": 1, "Economy": 5, "Society": 1, "Politics": 16, "Technology": 5}}') ON CONFLICT (id) 